f=Engineering/dana/custom/db-performance/SKILL.md · in=db-performance dana's query-and-storage tuning: finding slow queries, indexing what's actually queried, killing N+1 patterns, keeping datastore fast data grows measured, never guessed (axiom's discipline, data edition). It's empirical layer over data-modeling: model makes data correct, makes accessing fast. · p=Databases "fast enough dev" becomes "unusable production" query index table-scans 10M rows, N+1 fires query result, missing composite index. invisible dev-scale fatal production-scale. Measured tuning catches them before data does. · wu=Triggers: "slow query," "add index," "why database slow," "N+1," "optimize query," query growing table, ops monitoring showing latency, any read pattern justifying denormalization (data-modeling). · st:/ Protocol=`A query/data-access performance question \· -> MEASURE: the store's query plan (EXPLAIN-equivalent) + real timing at realistic scale \· (never index by guessing — measure what's actually slow, at production-like n) \· -> Diagnose: missing/wrong index \· full scan \· N+1 \· over-fetching \· bad join order \· lock contention \· -> Fix at the right layer: index (queried columns/paths) \· query rewrite \· model change \·` · in=**Read query plan before indexing.** store's EXPLAIN-equivalent shows what's actually happening full scan, missing index, bad join order. Adding indexes guessing creates write-cost storage read benefit (indexes aren't free; they slow writes). Measure first (axiom's rule). **Index what's queried, realistic scale.** columns/paths WHERE, JOIN, ORDER composite indexes order queries use. Test production-like index that's pointless rows decisive 10M, vice versa. **Kill N+1 explicitly.** pattern fetching results fires follow-up queries common ORM-induced killer. Batch, join, eager-load it's exactly kind thing agent-generated data access introduces silently (dev's review integrity; flag it). **Fix right layer.** Slow because missing index (add one), bad query (rewrite), wrong model (data-modeling change), genuinely much data (caching invalidation story, denormalization sync story). Don't cache around missing index. **Index changes migrations.** Adding/dropping index live store migration-discipline script operator runs (Rail large table, built concurrently/online avoid locking (store-specific, playbook). **Measure again, feed baselines.** Keep measured improvements (axiom); revert rest. real before/after numbers feed ops's monitoring baselines "normal" database dated fact, folklore. · of=`## DB Performance: [query/access] — [store] \· Query plan: [scan/index/join finding] \· Scale tested: [n] \· Diagnosis: [missing index / N+1 / over-fetch / bad join / contention] \· Fix: [index / rewrite / model / cache+invalidation / denormalize+sync] \· applied via [migration ref if schema/index] \· Before → after (at scale): [metric] → KEEP / REVERT \· → ops baseline [ref]` · pr=**Measure plan before indexing** guessed indexes cost writes read benefit., **Index what's queried, realistic scale** dev-scale hides truth ways., **N+1 default killer** batch/join/eager-load; agent code introduces silently., **Fix right layer** don't cache around missing index., **Index changes operator-run migrations** (Rail 3), online big tables., **Keep measured wins; feed baselines** real numbers, folklore. · f=production-scale data measure best available, label regime gap; don't declare query fast based dev-scale (data-modeling's evidence rule)., Store query-plan tool use timing model/complexity reasoning (axiom), labeled lower-fidelity., Caching proposed require explicit invalidation story; cache without invalidation correctness bug waiting happen. · b:with Other Skills=**data-modeling** (sibling): model tunes; denormalization decisions need skill's measured evidence., **migration-discipline** (sibling): index/schema changes ship operator-run scripts (Rail 3)., **axiom/performance-profiling**: measure-first discipline; DB-bound hot path found axiom's profiling routes here, benchmarks use axiom's record template., **ops/maintenance-hygiene**: latency baselines live there; regressions route diagnose., **raj**: N+1 over-fetching often originate API/ORM layer joint fixes.